    <article  class="views-row row-0 view-teaser-listing even">
  
    <div class="views-field views-field-field-image"><div class="field-content"><div class="floatelementright"><a href="https://theaterstudies.duke.edu/news/arts-advantage-nurturing-human-experience-through-theater-studies">  <img src="/sites/trinity.duke.edu/files/styles/landscape_small/public/Canfora%20Headshot.png?h=3b5d1417&amp;itok=2aUytB-b" width="300" height="225" alt="Madison Canfora" loading="lazy" class="image-style-landscape-small" />


</a></div></div></div><div class="views-field views-field-field-external-story"><div class="field-content"><div class="h4" role="heading" aria-level="2"><a href="https://theaterstudies.duke.edu/news/arts-advantage-nurturing-human-experience-through-theater-studies" class="external">The Arts Advantage: Nurturing the Human Experience Through Theater Studies<span class="visually-hidden"> (clicking this link will take you away from this site)</span></a></div></div></div><div class="views-field views-field-field-published-date"><div class="field-content h5"><time datetime="2022-02-24T15:23:31Z" class="datetime">February 24, 2022</time>
</div></div><div class="views-field views-field-nothing"><span class="field-content"><p>It was an incredibly busy and fruitful four years for Madison Canfora (B.S.&nbsp;Neuroscience, minors musical theater and&nbsp;Chemistry&nbsp;’21), who had already completed her pre-med track prior to graduating in December.

Through her mentorship with Dr. Monica Lemmon at the School of Medicine’s Department of Pediatrics, Canfora researched physician-patient communication in the neonatal intensive care unit and created an original codebook for brain imaging that screened data for relevant descriptions of brain imaging to… <a href="https://theaterstudies.duke.edu/news/arts-advantage-nurturing-human-experience-through-theater-studies">read&nbsp;more&nbsp;&raquo;<span class="visually-hidden"> about The Arts Advantage: Nurturing the Human Experience Through Theater Studies</span></a></p></span></div><div class="views-field views-field-edit-node"><span class="field-content"></span></div>

    </article>
  

    <article  class="views-row row-0 view-teaser-listing odd">
  
    <div class="views-field views-field-field-image"><div class="field-content"><div class="floatelementright"><a href="https://theaterstudies.duke.edu/news/arts-advantage-empathetic-engineers-thanks-theater">  <img src="/sites/trinity.duke.edu/files/styles/landscape_small/public/Santiago.jpeg?h=735f7c84&amp;itok=TMd54nS8" width="300" height="225" alt="Alexa Bolin Santiago" loading="lazy" class="image-style-landscape-small" />


</a></div></div></div><div class="views-field views-field-field-external-story"><div class="field-content"><div class="h4" role="heading" aria-level="2"><a href="https://theaterstudies.duke.edu/news/arts-advantage-empathetic-engineers-thanks-theater" class="external">Empathetic Engineers Thanks to Theater<span class="visually-hidden"> (clicking this link will take you away from this site)</span></a></div></div></div><div class="views-field views-field-field-published-date"><div class="field-content h5"><time datetime="2022-02-16T14:48:46Z" class="datetime">February 16, 2022</time>
</div></div><div class="views-field views-field-nothing"><span class="field-content"><p>STEAM student Alexa Bolin Santiago (B.S. Biomedical Engineering; minor musical theater ’23) is a biomedical engineering junior who is intrigued with automation, an interest that developed during her co-op work with Regeneron Pharmaceuticals.

With firm plans to focus on circuits, robotics and the medical application of programming, she’s also chosen to minor in musical theater and made room in her heavy course load to explore the world of theater design. <a href="https://theaterstudies.duke.edu/news/arts-advantage-empathetic-engineers-thanks-theater">read&nbsp;more&nbsp;&raquo;<span class="visually-hidden"> about Empathetic Engineers Thanks to Theater</span></a></p></span></div><div class="views-field views-field-edit-node"><span class="field-content"></span></div>

